name: Saltanat Mashirova
text: There are amazing OT Events such as S4, OTCEP Singapore, Industrial Security Conference CPH, Cybersecurity API, SANS ICS Summit, NightWatch,  etc. which mostly focuses giving and sharing knowledge with community with vendor neutral talks and only way to get there is to submit CFP which is usually reviewed thoroughly, but yes those are very tiny percentage of all of the conferences. Also agree with travel expenses, and virtual conferences helps here, but nothing replaces face to face. Therefore, hybrid will be more preferable, allowing people who can travel or from local community to come for face to face, and allow people who are other side of the globe to join virtually. Another point here is related to speaker you cannot talk all the time IT vs OT, and other basic things. It can be covered as Day 0 workshop, but in order to go to stage and share with community come up with your practical experience, actionable steps, pragmatic examples, new ideas, etc.

name: Saltanat Mashirova
text: AI offers numerous possibilities for both offensive and defensive purposes. However, as we are still in the initial stages of AI evolution, it is essential to conduct a thorough analysis of its potential applications and consider the associated risks. In the current global landscape, it is quite important to create an AI-supported attack and defense scenarios.

text: One of the areas I have seen is that the transformation doesn't include all stakeholders at the beginning of the project‚Äîoften the most important ones who will be affected by the change or the new systems, connections, etc. These members are often only brought in during the project rollout, which is way too late. Similar to this is pushing for transformation before considering cybersecurity risks. Therefore, cybersecurity risks must be baked in during the design phase and even more during the feed stage.

name: Saltanat Mashirova
text: I agree in terms of OT world is much larger. I have been involved  mostly in large installation which poses significant HSE risk including DCS and SCADA environments such as upstream, downstream, midstream, LNG, manufacturing, etc. and havent seen without AD. I do different types of assessment (cyber-physical risk, CSVA, gap, network, wireless, etc.) in large installations rather than audit, so that is most of my area of familiarity.  In terms of AD in DMZ it depends from the size, if it is big it all comes down to management.

name: Saltanat Mashirova
text: AD is most widely used in OT.  If you done your design smart (e.g. separate AD to PCN to Level 3, Level 2, no trust relationship with DMZ AD or IT AD)  and hardened AD, monitor it, then I don‚Äôt think it is huge mistake.

name: Satyavrat Thakur
text: Dharmendra Parakh Spot on.. and a great read!  We often talk about 'AI Safety,' but as CISOs and Cybersecurity Professionals, we need to talk about ‚ÄòAI and AI Agent Governance.‚Äô The shift from deterministic tools to probabilistic 'Security Actors' changes our entire trust model.  To answer your question: I see current state of majority AI systems stuck at Authorization. It‚Äôs one thing to give an agent an identity, it‚Äôs another to ensure its reasoning stays within the bounds of least privilege in real-time. We‚Äôre moving from static RBAC to dynamic, intent-based signals.

name: Satyavrat Thakur
text: Absolutely agreed, Beata.   A CISO without budget, authority, and decision-making power is a title without impact. I‚Äôve seen how security initiatives fail when they compete with broader IT priorities, leaving the CISO accountable but powerless.   Empowering CISOs with direct control and executive backing is not optional, it‚Äôs the foundation of real cyber resilience.

name: Satyavrat Thakur
text: Rightly pointed Beata Kaminski   Building a culture where all the IT team members, from management down, collaborate extensively with Cybersecurity teams, and feel empowered to ask questions and flag risks is key. text: What if attackers use portable versions (which I have seen many times) of these software? I know WinRAR portable stores settings in a .ini file, but does it write them in the registry actively? or maybe only temporarily? They will surely leave traces of execution and interaction with system components, but will it also store keys for recently accessed or created RAR files?
position: Director of Incident Response & Threat Hunting

name: Pere C.
text: I would say this is not a new attack vector coming up, it has just been ‚Äúrevived‚Äù and it is making a comeback in the last years. For instance, in 2017, AV researchers from Sophos or Lookout uncovered malware targeting Android devices, which was distributed through seemingly legitimate applications on the Google Play Store. Some of those malicious mobile apps were using 3rd-party development libraries that facilitated malvertisement campaigns. In response to such threats, both Google and Apple did take significant measures to enhance the security of their app stores, including the removal of malicious applications and the implementation of more stringent security protocols to prevent the distribution of malicious apps. It is perfectly possible that priorities have shifted internally in the last few years for those app stores and this vigilance has become more lax.  When it comes to state sponsored attacks, this is yet again nothing new. The most advanced APT groups have all targeted mobile devices even in the past few years (Pegasus spyware by NSO Group, APT42 targeting USA political candidates, or APT29 watering hole attacks targeting mobile devices).
position: Director of Incident Response & Threat Hunting

name: Mohanasundaram Adaikkappan
text: Based on a recent report from Google, they have banned 158,000 bad developer accounts and prevented 2.36 million policy-violating apps from being published on Google Play.  https://security.googleblog.com/2025/01/how-we-kept-google-play-android-app-ecosystem-safe-2024.html  And yes, many organizations still underestimate the importance of mobile security. There is an increase in targeting individuals through personal accounts, such as contacting individuals through LinkedIn for job offers, impersonating CEOs via Google Email, deploying infostealers on personal devices, and stealing credentials from personal password managers and mobile devices, especially by North Korean threat actors.  Organizations should provide and fully manage mobile devices using MDM solutions. At a minimum, enterprise applications and device passcode age/length should be managed/protected by the organization.  Additionally, organizations should promote the use of subscriptions like the Microsoft Workplace Discount Program, which offers Microsoft Defender for mobile devices.

name: Pere C.
text: I agree with most statements from Florian Roth, and I would add a fourth point: 4. Attribution is one of the most difficult things within the defensive side of cyber security, and yet this is all nearly every is most interested in doing (increases reputation, this is one of the few things non-technical stakeholders do understand and improves labeling and marketization). In the end, attribution is especially important for countries who defend against APT nation state threat actors, but for the rest it is definitely not among the most important items they need to know; TTPs and IOCs are much more important.  The best book, in my opinion, out there about attribution is written by a German called Timo Steffens: "Attribution of Advanced Persisten Threats". He ends the conclusion of his book with a sentence from someone else called Thomas Rid: "There is always someone who knows if the attribution is correct".  Meanwhile, attribution will keep being bloody difficult and complex.
position: Director of Incident Response & Threat Hunting

name: Pere C.
text: This seems like a great and valuable work, Koen Van Impe. CTI is and has always been a very difficult topic and resource to demonstrate and "sell" the value of to non-technical C-level managers within this field. I see CTI as traders see the trading market and the economy: a field which usually gives global ROI if you stick to a proper strategy in the long term. Nevertheless, some CTI aspects can give immediate return that is visible, while others can give long-term return that is difficult to make it tangible to executives. If I were you I would add one aspect in your work to prove the value of CTI which focuses on time (I know that you kind of have this with the Strategic/Operational/Tactical differentiation, but not totally nor very defined in terms of time or impact (Immediate Impact, Mid-term Impact, Long-term Impact).

text: Hey Rob, thanks for this insights, however I do disagree with your statement "this attack .. could have been prevented by simply subscribing to a $57 monthly license that offers more comprehensive safety features". Advanced security logging features or advanced security features in general do not automatically translate in being able to detect or prevent sophisticated attacks, There is a lot of effort that must go into how you configure, operate and monitor these advanced security features to be able to detect and eventually - prevent - sophisticated attacks, at least this is the way I see it. Purchasing a license alone, without considering people and processes' pillars that must be attached to it, will do very little to benefit organizations' security posture.

name: Dinesh Reddy
text: Absolutely agree with this perspective. But the real challenge often lies in leadership. Many SOCs are led by managers who lack deep cybersecurity expertise or vision - they treat the SOC like any other operational unit, focusing on alert counts, incident volume, polished dashboards, and KPIs that look good on paper but don‚Äôt improve real security outcomes.  In my view, a truly effective SOC needs a strong balance of People, Process, and Technology (PPT). Unfortunately, this balance is often missing. The best SOCs are not just reactive - they should spend more than half their time being proactive: hunting threats, fine-tuning detections, and building stronger defenses to reduce alert fatigue.  Also, adopting a structured tiered approach like defense-in-depth can make a huge difference. L1 analysts can handle the bulk of alerts, while senior analysts focus on deeper investigations and continuous improvement. The goal should be not just to operate, but to evolve.

name: Hishan Shouketh

text: Thanks for sharing your thoughts on the alleged Oracle Cloud breach!   I agree that the authenticity of the hacker‚Äôs claims is still up in the air and hasn‚Äôt been fully confirmed. That said, there‚Äôs one detail that caught my attention: the hacker uploaded a text file to the Oracle Cloud platform, which includes their contact information. This suggests they may have had some level of access, so I wouldn‚Äôt dismiss it as fake just yet.  At the same time, this alone doesn‚Äôt prove the breach is real. It‚Äôs definitely worth digging deeper to verify what‚Äôs going on.   Looking forward to seeing more updates as the investigation unfolds‚Äîcurious to hear your take as more details come to light!

text: Thanks for sharing this thought-provoking article on false flag cyber operations! As a CTI professional, I find it incredibly insightful. False flag tactics add a layer of complexity to attribution, challenging our ability to accurately identify threat actors. This article by Warner Chad delves into the indicators and motivations behind these operations, providing valuable knowledge for enhancing our cyber defense strategies. A must-read for fellow CTI practitioners  #threatintelligence #CTI

name: Praveen Singh
text: Thank you for your comment! I completely agree that it's crucial to assess the organization's maturity and readiness when implementing threat intelligence tools. It's also important to note that threat intelligence is not a silver bullet and should be part of a comprehensive cybersecurity strategy that includes prevention, detection, response, and recovery.  As you pointed out, there's a growing concern about rebalancing detection and response to prepare and prevent. Investing in threat intelligence is a step in the right direction, but it's just one piece of the puzzle. By taking a holistic approach to cybersecurity, we can better prepare and prevent cyber threats before they occur, ultimately reducing the need for detection and response. Thanks again for your insightful comment!

text: GDPR compliance focuses on personal data protection, while an infosec law covers a wider range of risks. So saying that GDPR compliant law should have been discussed and adopted first only means this lady has no idea what she's talking about. These laws should complement each other, with risk identification and management underpinning both. Moreover, it's generally a very good idea for CIRT to distance itself. Cybersecurity doesn't belong there and it was in a conflict of interest for a long time and actually crippled the government with it's inability, and probably lack of will to enforce the law.  To add on this, in successful models worldwide governments recognize the value of private-sector expertise, particularly in areas like cybersecurity. Unfortunately all Montenegrin government officials I spoke to are dismissing this idea of private-public partnerships. Nobody answered why.

name: Athira R P
text: I have always been fascinated by the police force‚Äîtheir vigilance, investigative skills, and dedication to maintaining peace in society. This admiration led me to ask: In the digital world, who ensures safety? When I discovered cybersecurity years later, I knew it was my calling. Without hesitation, I pursued it for my post-graduation. Now, with five years of experience in Incident Response, Threat Analysis, and Threat Hunting, my passion remains strong. Every security incident is a learning opportunity, revealing new attack patterns. Identifying an incident, tracking the attacker's path to initial access, and evicting them is a thrill. Closing security gaps ensures they don‚Äôt return. Early threat detection provides financial stability and customer confidence. I also take on responsibilities beyond threat handling‚Äîguiding customers, mentoring teams, and leading operations. I believe in giving back to the community, volunteering with law enforcement, and spreading cybersecurity awareness. Educating individuals is as important as technical defenses. In this ever-evolving field, continuous learning is key. The satisfaction of defending organizations and securing critical services keeps me motivated every day. #WomenInCyber #ShePwns

name: Juan Pablo Betancourt
text: Jan Ogorzalek excellent point. In my opinion a SIEM or XDR that owns a data pipeline is a in conflict of interest. Do they really optimize collection and hurt their own ingestion?  I suspect those "acquisitions" are not to really have data pipelines but to close gaps fast in collection capabilities. Ask some CS or Chronicle clients how bad was log ingestion and data filtering 1 year ago before the adquisitions.  Organizations I know that maximize security data pipeline capabiltiies make it independent from SIEM with players like CRIBL, Tenzir, Observo, Databahn, etc.

name: Juan Pablo Betancourt
text: Ruslan Omarov Fabiano Santana - CISM absolutely, the difference its always in execution. To maximize a SIEM you need solid SOC functions: threat intel to drive detection roadmaps and hunting, telemetry governance via data pipelines to optimize cost and support detection, detectio engineering to deploy fast and control the noise and solid triage and investigation to make use of the alerts.  It's not easy and that's why for several organizations XDR with threat Intel infusioned and detection engineering via vendor are sometimes the best they can do

name: Juan Pablo Betancourt
text: √ñzmert Lalik challenge is that cyberdefense ecosystem is already complex with several vendors to manage...adding another solution to maximize it's not easy.  The benefit it's clear but requires maturity

name: Juan Pablo Betancourt
text: Naveed Hamid agree on the need to decouple collection layer from analytical layer. But it's something that it's usually higher in the maturity pyramid hence not broadly adopted.  Let's hope it gets more traction.

text: I agree with Muhammad Ali Azeem. The sensors send their data to a PLC. name: Saltanat Mashirova
text: Great post, Matt. Even with interlocks in place (mechanical, electrical, or logical), controls remains essential. Why? Because interlocks can be bypassed, intentionally or accidentally, and cyber compromise of field controllers or logic can defeat them. As you rightly said, the last line of defense is the human, and that‚Äôs not reliable enough alone. Also, risk tolerance criteria in industrial plants are based on consequence severity, not the cause. So if a cyberattack can lead to the same outcome as a process safety failure, it must meet the same risk criteria. This means cybersecurity protections need to reduce the likelihood of loss events to the same thresholds defined in HAZOP/LOPA, even if the consequence is triggered differently. In short: interlocks are necessary, but not sufficient. Cyber and safety must be assessed together, not in silos.

name: Dalibor Jeremic
text: Dear Team, I am reaching out as a loyal customer of over 10 years to express my concern regarding the recent cancellation of my Mastercard credit card in mid-August due to an outstanding balance of approximately AED 3,000.  What troubles me most is that I received no prior notification‚Äîno SMS, email, WhatsApp message, or call from my relationship manager‚Äîbefore the cancellation.   Despite multiple inquiries, I have yet to receive a clear explanation as to why no warning was issued.  Since then, I‚Äôve been trying to reinstate my credit card, but the process has been unnecessarily complicated and frustrating. Considering my long-standing history with your institution and a spotless payment record, I find it disappointing to be treated as if I were a new client. Even my relationship manager has been unable to expedite the process. Is this truly the level of service extended to loyal clients over a relatively minor amount?  I kindly request that this matter be reviewed with urgency and that appropriate steps be taken to restore my card and ensure better communication moving forward. Thank you for your attention.

I was forced to take a Taxi home as transportation did not operate at 00:30 anymore....  Taxi costs 85EURO. Lufthansa wants to pay 50EUR only. Again i had no other chance to get home...  Lufthansa wants to improve his customer satisfaction, after reading this you should know where to start with...   I will do my best not taking Lufthansa anymore!!!!

name: Mansour Al Blooshi
text: The unsaid truth about procurement professionals.  We never studied procurement at our colleges. Most of them didn‚Äôt have soft skills and they gained it by their own by experience or short training courses. Procurement professionals ended up here because they loved what they do. In my experience I found many colleagues either they love procurement or they hate it, there is no other options. if you say you are working just to be paid salary. You won‚Äôt survive because the expectation what you need to deliver for the business.  All these expectations still some companies under estimate their procurement.

name: Mansour Al Blooshi
text: At End of the year, most of the departments the budget team initiates planning for the budget with all departments except procurement. If you ask for training purposes, they will tell you, it is already budgeted with HR and check with them. Then you are surprised that assigned budget did not serve to equip your one employee as per your strategy.  I‚Äôm not generalizing, but talking behalf of majority.  Thanks again Karima Zaghrioui these posts are really meaningful for us.

name: Elvis Louis Cardoso
text: With advancements in technology, many organizations are moving toward more integrated, data-driven procurement systems. These systems allow for greater flexibility in managing contracts, purchase orders (POs), and payments in real-time. Modern procurement solutions can track purchases from multiple sources, ensuring that approvals are made before payments are processed while offering a more streamlined and agile process.

text: Sam Wallace hallucinations are already a problem with LLMs mate. If we think within the AI context, Retrieval Augmentation of data sources could be a solution, provided these data sources are continuously updated. However, speaking from a Vulnerability Management POV, we already have dedicated tools that take care of the problem. Even these sophisticated tools sometimes release the CVE specific plugins with some latency because of the time required by them to research the CVEs & develop detection signatures & RegEx for those vulnerabilities!

name: Sudharshan Kumar
text: Sam Wallace that‚Äôs a valid question! I guess this gap could be bridged using RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation) in LLMs. RAG LLMs could be a thing to solve such problems.

name: Sudharshan Kumar
text: B ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî Reasoning: E2EE will encrypt the message data and not the routing information such as Source/Destination IP addresses. Whereas, Link Encryption encrypts the entire packet but the data are available unencrypted at the intermediate nodes. Encryption ensures Confidentiality of data. Option C mentions about Integrity which requires a signature or hash checksum to verify the integrity which is not part of these 2 encryption types under discussion. Assuming this reasoning is valid, the answer would be option B.

name: Sudharshan Kumar
text: B. SYN cookies and timeout on ACK wait period.  Assumptions: Options C and D recommend to apply timeout on SYN which isn't possible as it is the initial Request from client which the server has no control over.  Option A recommends to use ACK cookies which again increases dependency on the ACK packet to occur which could in turn be exploited.

text: Big thanks for sharing, Abhijith! This is a compelling reminder that default configurations of off-the-shelf security products are no match for today‚Äôs ransomware actors. The threat landscape is evolving rapidly, and defenders must move beyond reactive tools to proactive, behavior-driven strategies. It also underscore the importance of understanding adversary tactics in depth. Even basic evasion techniques can reveal critical gaps in detection and response. It is really interesting to see your ransomware emulation program focused to this very issue.  Wishing you the best for your DEFCON training!   #CyberSecurity #Ransomware #AdversaryEmulation #IncidentResponse #DEFCON #ThreatDetection #PurpleTeam

text: It's an interesting perspective Ricki Burke and I am seeing more and more CVs written like the example you gave. It certainly helps to catch the eyes and push on top of the stack. But here's another side of it. I asked some candidates about the methodology and KPIs they used for the quantification of the impact they mentioned in the CV and none of them were able to justify or even explain that number logically. While these carefully crafted statements help the candidate get past the ATS or recruitment HR level, it makes them look shallow when these numbers are not coming from and actual metrics. It would be great if you could suggest some tools or techniques that candidates can use even at personal level to create this type of metrics and support their statement written in the CV during the interview.

text: I suggest this path based on my experience and observations:  1. Start building your brand (github, blogs, meetups, presentations etc.) 2. text: Weather Center: Cloud seeding didn't contribute to UAE storms  The UAE‚Äôs weather bureau has confirmed that no cloud-seeding missions occurred during Tuesday‚Äôs torrential rain.  An official for the National Centre of Meteorology confirmed that its seeding planes had not conducted flights after heavy rain inundated parts of the country.  Many people had speculated on social media that the country‚Äôs cloud seeding program was in some way responsible for the deluge. The confirmation enforces the NCM‚Äôs previously stated policy that volatile weather systems are too dangerous to dispatch seeding planes to.  ‚ÄúSome say we are responsible for storms. We are not responsible for this,‚Äù an NCM forecaster previously told¬†The National. ‚ÄúAircraft do not go inside storm clouds if they are strong or dangerous,‚Äù the forecaster said.  The NCM previously said the adverse weather resulted from a low-pressure system moving towards the Emirates.

text: It‚Äôs a collaborative learning model that is in place. In today‚Äôs classroom, a teacher spends 90% of the time in preparing and delivering the content that a search engine like Google can provide. She has no time for the child, who is just considered an empty vessel that can be filled with any content. With the humanoid robot taking over the role of delivering content, the teacher can teach what Google can‚Äôt. She mentors kids, teaches them how to learn, provides emotional support and ignites an entrepreneurial mindset. The robot can provide what Google does, along with formative and summative assessments. Meanwhile, students can aim at self-directed learning and design thinking. The teacher orchestrates the whole classroom.

name: Victoria Komolafe
text: This is such an important point you have both highlighted. Innovation isn‚Äôt progress if it only shifts inequity from ‚Äúignored‚Äù to ‚Äúpriced out.‚Äù  Femtech has huge potential to correct decades of under-representation in women‚Äôs health, but only if accessibility, reimbursement models, and public/ private adoption are designed in from day one. Otherwise, we risk creating parallel systems where early detection and personalised care become a luxury, not a standard.  Equity has to be a design principle, not an afterthought.

name: Victoria Komolafe
text: Great read Ahmed Osman  Abu Dhabi‚Äôs approach is a strong example of how digital health can move systems from reactive care to predictive and preventive models at scale. The integration of AI, genomics, and real-time data through platforms like Malaffi shows what‚Äôs possible when governance, interoperability and population health strategy are aligned. A compelling blueprint for health systems globally.

name: Victoria Komolafe
text: Congratulations Ola Oladiran, BSc, FCCA, CertBALM¬Æ üôåüèæ

name: Victoria Komolafe
text: I agree Rita! The issue is not AI itself,   it‚Äôs how we operationalise accountability. AI doesn‚Äôt need entirely new inspection models to scale; it needs to be embedded into existing clinical and risk frameworks with clear boundaries.  Where AI fails, is when it is treated as a standalone innovation. Where it works, is when it is delivered as a governed service: defined clinical ownership, human-in-the-loop by design, auditable decision points and clear escalation paths.  Progress will not come from waiting for inspection models to change, but from translating AI capability into forms regulators already understand. That are safety, accountability and controlled.

name: Victoria Komolafe
text: AI is undoubtedly improving healthcare outcomes, but scaling innovation without governance simply scales risk. In healthcare, where data can‚Äôt be replaced and systems are deeply interconnected, weak oversight has consequences far beyond a single breach.  Governance has to be built in, not bolted on.

name: Victoria Komolafe
text: Great perspective Michael.  AI is not here to replace project managers, it‚Äôs here to elevate the role.  In my experience working across healthcare IT, digital transformation, and now cybersecurity, AI has become a powerful enabler. It takes on the repetitive, time-consuming tasks, which frees PMs to focus on what truly drives outcomes: stakeholder engagement, clarity of vision, and human-centred leadership.  I have seen this firsthand in healthcare projects where AI supports scheduling, documentation, and risk insights, allowing teams to move faster without losing the human connection that is vital in clinical environments.  AI may be the engine, but strong leadership remains the steering wheel.

name: Victoria Komolafe
text: Great work, Soud! Cybersecurity in healthcare is such a critical and rapidly evolving area, especially as digital transformation accelerates across hospitals and clinical systems.  I really like how your project covers both current threats like ransomware and phishing, as well as emerging defense opportunities such as AI-driven detection and blockchain. Understanding these risks is essential for protecting patient data and ensuring safe, uninterrupted care delivery.  Well done on shedding light on an area that deserves continued focus in the region and beyond.

The recent OCI deployments at Burjeel and King‚Äôs College Hospital Dubai show how cloud can drive reliability, interoperability, and readiness for AI-led care.  For anyone working in EMR or clinical informatics, building cloud fundamentals (OCI, AWS, Azure) alongside workflow expertise is quickly becoming a real advantage.

A powerful step toward easing burnout and restoring balance in clinical practice.

name: Ahmed Mazhar
text: Hey Mark,  Great summary and insights. A quick point to align on NIA‚Äôs intent:  NIA aims to automate and streamline compliance workflows, not replace internal controls. It combines structured self-assessment with evidence collection and selective validation to support ongoing assurance, not just a point-in-time check. In addition to that, it integrates with multiple data sources to rationalize the compliance scores and provide proper reasoning on a sub control level. For example, Threat Intelligence feeds and SOC feeds.   It emphasizes real-time dashboards, continuous monitoring, and transparent audit trails to reduce sampling bias and improve traceability.  You‚Äôre right that no framework is immune to human factors. NIA‚Äôs value proposition is to push toward more automated, repeatable processes and continuous attestation, while staying within the legal/regulatory requirements and enabling deeper visibility where needed.  On enforcement, the platform is designed to enhance oversight and accountability, not replace the need for robust internal controls. It seeks to minimize the ‚Äúhonesty ceiling‚Äù by making evidence collection, verification, and remediation more transparent and auditable.  Thank you üôèüèº

text: All the best Khalid  Some suggestions from my end I hope it helps:  1- create a team and distribute tasks amoung of them, which could be from procurement, IT, operation, etc.  2- Never find a solution when there is no problem.
